SIMPLE: fleer
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: fleer
<hw>fle"er</hw> <pr>(fl⟦emac⟧"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who
flees.</def> <rj><au>Ld. Berners.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fleer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: fleer
<hw>fleer</hw> <pr>(fl⟦emac⟧r)</pr>, <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>fleered</conjf> <pr>(fl⟦emac⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>fleering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>flerien</ets>; cf.
Scot. <ets>fleyr</ets>, Norw. <ets>flira</ets> to titter, giggle, laugh
at nothing, MHG. <ets>vlerre</ets>, <ets>vlarre</ets>, a wide
wound.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a wry face in contempt, or to
grin in scorn; to deride; to sneer; to mock; to gibe; <as>as, to
<ex>fleer</ex> and flout</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>fleer</qex> and scorn at our solemnity.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To grin with an air of civility; to leer.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grinning and <qex>fleering</qex> as though they went to a bear
baiting.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fleer
<hw>Fleer</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To mock; to flout at.</def>
<rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fleer
<hw>Fleer</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A word or look of
derision or mockery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And mark the <qex>fleers</qex>, the gibes, and notable scorn.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A grin of civility; a leer.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sly, treacherous <qex>fleer</qex> on the face of deceivers.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fleerer</ent>⟦br⟧
